               Irenaeus Martyr thus;
                  An. 172. As the Euchariſt conſiſting of two natures, the earthly and the heauenly,


ſo our Bodies, &c.

Epiphanius thus;
   An. 379. Chriſt ſpeaking of a loafe which is round in figure, and cannot ſee, heare, nor feele, ſaith of it, This is my Body.


In Anchor.

               Gelaſius thus;
                  An. 490. By the Sacraments


we are made partakers of the heauenly nature and yet for all that ceaſeth not the nature of bread and wine. Contra Eutichenſ.
